<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-partial-elasticity">
  <title>Partial elasticity</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Measure how a multivariable function changes when only one input varies.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret partial derivatives visually using traces with one variable held constant.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Compute partial derivatives by treating other variables as fixed and applying single-variable rules.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Recall single-variable elasticity: <m>\rdv{y}{x} = \dfrac{\dd{y}/y}{\dd{x}/x} = \DS\dv{y}{x}\cdot\frac{x}{y}</m>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Define partial elasticity of <m>z=f(x,y)</m> with respect to <m>x</m> as
            <me>
                \rpdv{z}{x} = \frac{\rd_x z}{\rd x} = \frac{\mathrm{d}_x{z}/z}{\dd{x}/x} = \pdv{z}{x}\cdot\frac{x}{z}
            </me>
            and with respect to <m>y</m> as
            <me>
                \rpdv{z}{y} = \frac{\rd_y z}{\rd y} = \frac{\mathrm{d}_y{z}/z}{\dd{y}/y} = \pdv{z}{y}\cdot\frac{y}{z}
            </me>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            A rate law for a chemical reaction might be <m>r = k [A]^{\alpha} [B]^{\beta}</m>, where <m>[A]</m> and <m>[B]</m> are concentrations of reactants.
            Then the partial elasticity of the rate with respect to <m>[A]</m> is
            <me>
                \rpdv{r}{[A]} = \alpha
            </me>
            and the partial elasticity of the rate with respect to <m>[B]</m> is
            <me>
                \rpdv{r}{[B]} = \beta
            </me>.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, if <m>r = k [A]^{2} [B]^{3}</m>, then the partial elasticity with respect to <m>[A]</m> is 2 and the partial elasticity with respect to <m>[B]</m> is 3. This means that a 1% increase in <m>[A]</m> will lead to a 2% increase in the reaction rate, while a 1% increase in <m>[B]</m> will lead to a 3% increase in the reaction rate.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Utility function in economics: <m>z = U(x,y)</m>, where <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are quantities of two goods.
            Then the partial elasticity of utility with respect to good 1 is
            <me>
                \rpdv{U}{x} = \pdv{U}{x}\cdot\frac{x}{U}
            </me>
            and the partial elasticity of utility with respect to good 2 is
            <me>
                \rpdv{U}{y} = \pdv{U}{y}\cdot\frac{y}{U}
            </me>.
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Cobb-Douglas production function: <m>z = A K^{\alpha} L^{\beta}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Here, <m>K</m> and <m>L</m> are inputs (capital and labor), and <m>A</m> is total factor productivity.
        </p>
        <p>
            Partial elasticities: <m>\DS\rpdv{z}{K} = \alpha</m> and <m>\DS\rpdv{z}{L} = \beta</m>
        </p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>
            Suppose two goods have quantities demanded given by <m>q_1=f(p_1,p_2)</m> and <m>q_2=g(p_1,p_2)</m>, where <m>p_1</m> and <m>p_2</m> are their prices.
            Then the cross-price elasticity of demand for good 1 with respect to the price of good 2 is
            <me>
                \rpdv{q_1}{p_2} = \pdv{q_1}{p_2}\cdot\frac{p_2}{q_1}
            </me>
            and the own-price elasticity of demand for good 1 is
            <me>
                \rpdv{q_1}{p_1} = \pdv{q_1}{p_1}\cdot\frac{p_1}{q_1}
            </me>.
        </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
